docs.abstract: The president has sought to ally himself with Middle Eastern leaders, but at home, he has seemingly made little attempt to repair his fractured relationship with Muslim Americans.
docs.snippet: The president has sought to ally himself with Middle Eastern leaders, but at home, he has seemingly made little attempt to repair his fractured relationship with Muslim Americans.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The White House’s guest list last week for President Trump’s first dinner celebrating the Muslim holy month of Ramadan included a who’s who of diplomats from the Middle East. But the event turned out to be more notable for who apparently was not there: representatives from Muslim American groups.

headline.main: On Islam, Trump Takes a Different Approach at Home and Abroad
headline.print_headline: As Trump Woos Middle Eastern Leaders, Muslim Americans Feel Scorned

docs.abstract: The new leader of the commission’s consumer protection unit was part of a legal team that defended a payday lender hit with a $1.3 billion fraud settlement by the F.T.C.
docs.snippet: The new leader of the commission’s consumer protection unit was part of a legal team that defended a payday lender hit with a $1.3 billion fraud settlement by the F.T.C.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The new director of the Federal Trade Commission’s consumer protection unit, a watchdog with broad investigative powers over private companies, stands out even in an administration prone to turning over regulatory authority to pro-industry players.

headline.main: A Lawyer for Payday Lenders Is Confirmed for F.T.C. Job
headline.print_headline: Lawyer for Payday Lenders Will Lead Consumer Protection Unit

byline.original: By Glenn Thrush and Jack Nicas

docs.abstract: After refusing at her confirmation hearing to condemn the C.I.A.’s use of torture after 9/11, she wrote in a letter that the agency should not have undertaken that program.
docs.snippet: After refusing at her confirmation hearing to condemn the C.I.A.’s use of torture after 9/11, she wrote in a letter that the agency should not have undertaken that program.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Gina Haspel, President Trump’s nominee to lead the C.I.A., appeared on Tuesday to have secured the votes to be confirmed after she declared that the agency should not have undertaken its interrogation program in which Qaeda detainees were tortured after the Sept. 11 attacks. She had refused to condemn the program at her confirmation hearing last week.

headline.main: Gina Haspel Likely to Be Confirmed as C.I.A. Chief After Repudiating Torture
headline.print_headline: Haspel Rejects C.I.A. Torture, Securing Votes

docs.abstract: The promotion of Mr. Muzinich, who spent most of his career on Wall Street, elevates a moderate voice within the Trump economic team.
docs.snippet: The promotion of Mr. Muzinich, who spent most of his career on Wall Street, elevates a moderate voice within the Trump economic team.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Monday will tap Justin Muzinich, a top aide to Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin, as the Treasury Department’s deputy secretary, a powerful role that includes overseeing a broad portfolio of policy matters like taxes, financial regulation, trade and economic sanctions.

headline.main: Treasury’s Tax Law Architect, Justin Muzinich, Is Tapped as Deputy Secretary
headline.print_headline: Trump Elevates Tax-Law Architect Into Deputy Role at Treasury

docs.abstract: Charles P. Rettig is a longtime tax lawyer who has specialized in defending people and companies against the agency.
docs.snippet: Charles P. Rettig is a longtime tax lawyer who has specialized in defending people and companies against the agency.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s nominee to lead the Internal Revenue Service is a longtime tax lawyer who has specialized in defending people and companies against the tax agency in court.

headline.main: To Lead I.R.S., Trump Nominates Lawyer Who Battled It
headline.print_headline: Nominee For I.R.S. Fought Against It

docs.abstract: A closely watched clash between federal prosecutors and Microsoft fizzled after Congress enacted a new law last month.
docs.snippet: A closely watched clash between federal prosecutors and Microsoft fizzled after Congress enacted a new law last month.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court announced on Tuesday that it would not decide whether federal prosecutors can force Microsoft to turn over digital data stored outside the United States. The move followed arguments in the case in February and the enactment of a new federal law that both sides said made the case moot.

headline.main: Supreme Court Tosses Out Microsoft Case on Digital Data Abroad

docs.abstract: A Georgetown professor received a worldwide response to his monthlong call to limit online time, but that was just the beginning of the challenge.
docs.snippet: A Georgetown professor received a worldwide response to his monthlong call to limit online time, but that was just the beginning of the challenge.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As part of a monthlong challenge to declutter her digital life, Kristi Kremers vowed she would cut off her online addictions: Instagram, Facebook and the news websites she checks hourly.

headline.main: A Call to Cut Back Online Addictions. Pitted Against Just One More Click.
headline.print_headline: Answering Call to Limit Daily Digital Diet in a World That Gorges on Social Media

docs.abstract: A look at the legal questions raised by President Trump’s unconventional use of his constitutional power to pardon federal crimes.
docs.snippet: A look at the legal questions raised by President Trump’s unconventional use of his constitutional power to pardon federal crimes.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump’s use of his constitutional power to pardon criminals is proving to be as idiosyncratic as other aspects of his presidency. On Thursday, he pardoned Dinesh D’Souza, a conservative author convicted of making illegal campaign contributions, and he said he was considering commuting the sentence of former Gov. Rod R. Blagojevich of Illinois, a Democrat, and pardoning Martha Stewart, the lifestyle guru.

headline.main: How Far Can Trump Go in Issuing Pardons?

docs.abstract: The first lady accompanied the president on a visit to FEMA after President Trump bitterly attacked the news media on Twitter for being “unfair and vicious to my wife.”
docs.snippet: The first lady accompanied the president on a visit to FEMA after President Trump bitterly attacked the news media on Twitter for being “unfair and vicious to my wife.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — After spending nearly a month out of the public eye, Melania Trump emerged from the White House on Wednesday, putting an end to at least a few of the theories — some her husband has repeated to his 52 million Twitter followers — that blossomed like swampland ragweed during her time in seclusion.

headline.main: Melania Trump Appears in Public After ‘a Little Rough Patch’
headline.print_headline: First Lady Resurfaces After ‘a Little Rough Patch’

docs.abstract: President Trump is calling the chief of staff he pushed out, Reince Priebus, to complain about John Kelly, the chief of staff who took Mr. Priebus’s place.
docs.snippet: President Trump is calling the chief of staff he pushed out, Reince Priebus, to complain about John Kelly, the chief of staff who took Mr. Priebus’s place.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Among the many people agitated this week over John F. Kelly, the White House chief of staff, was President Trump. And among the people the president called to express dissatisfaction, according to those close to him, was none other than Reince Priebus, the previous chief of staff, who also irritated Mr. Trump.

headline.main: Unwelcome Attention for John Kelly, the Man Enlisted to Bring Calm
headline.print_headline: Unwelcome Attention  For Man Who Came In To Calm Things Down

byline.original: By Peter Baker and Maggie Haberman
